          "body": "The chapter's emotional and theological pivot is compressed into a single verse: 'When the king heard the words of the book of the law, he tore his clothes' (22:11). In the ancient Near East and throughout the Hebrew Bible, tearing one's garment is the embodied language of grief too large for words — Jacob tears his clothes at the reported death of Joseph (Gen 37:34), the high priest tears his clothes at what he considers blasphemy (Mark 14:63), Hezekiah tears his clothes at Sennacherib's taunt (2 Kings 19:1). What is distinctive about Josiah's response is its immediate connection to the words of the text. He does not tear his clothes when the scroll is found; he tears them when the scroll is read. The words do the work. Chuck Swindoll notes the pastoral implication: the response of genuine conviction is visceral, not merely intellectual — the Word read aloud breaks through the surface of managed piety into the actual life. Josiah's reaction is the model the chapter holds up: when the gap between what God requires and what has been done becomes audible, the right response is not explanation but mourning."
