          "title": "Huldah's bifurcated oracle — 22:14-20",
          "body": "The theological center of the chapter is the oracle delivered by Huldah the prophetess, and its structure is deliberately asymmetrical. The first word (vv. 16-17) is for 'this place and its inhabitants' — irreversible judgment, grounded in a clear covenant-lawsuit: forsaking God, burning incense to other gods, provoking His wrath (22:17). The wrath that burns will not be quenched. No amount of subsequent repentance is offered as an escape clause. This is the chapter's most sobering theological claim: there is a point at which generational covenant-breaking fills a cup that cannot be emptied by one penitent king. Huldah's second word (vv. 18-20) is for Josiah personally — and it is separated from the first by a deliberate 'but' (22:18). The personal oracle is grounded not in his reforms or his administrative faithfulness but in the condition of his heart: 'your heart was tender and you humbled yourself before the LORD' (22:19). Douglas Moo's observation about Romans 2:4-5 — that the hardness or softness of the heart determines one's relationship to divine kindness — is anticipated here by centuries. God truly hears (shama) the tender heart. The promise is not immunity from all suffering — Josiah dies at Megiddo in 609 BC (23:29-30) — but death in peace, meaning death without seeing the destruction of Jerusalem. His eyes are sheltered from the worst of what his nation will experience."
