          "body": "That Hilkiah, Ahikam, Achbor, Shaphan, and Asaiah go to Huldah rather than to Jeremiah or Zephaniah (both active in this period) is one of the chapter's most arresting details. Huldah is one of only four women in the Hebrew Bible explicitly designated as neviah (prophetess — alongside Miriam, Deborah, and Isaiah's wife), and she is consulted by the full weight of the royal and priestly establishment without any trace of hesitation or protest. Her oracle carries the standard prophetic messenger formula ('thus says the LORD God of Israel,' 22:15, 18) — the same formula Isaiah, Jeremiah, and Amos use. Calvin notes that God distributes His gifts sovereignly and without regard to human expectation; here He places His authoritative word in the mouth of a woman whose husband was keeper of the royal wardrobe. The Deuteronomistic Historian records her words without apology or explanation. The chapter's implicit teaching is that prophetic authority is not a function of gender or social position but of divine commissioning — and the commissioned word, whoever carries it, must be received."
